line_1: If to thyself thou canst thyself acquit,
line_2: In spite of Dullness, and in spite of Wit,

line_1: Why charge we heav'n in those, in these acquit?
line_2: In both, to reason right, is to submit.

line_1: From many Dangers must themselves acquit,
line_2: And more than Scylla and Charibdis meet;

line_1: And Duty, long as Life, must study to acquit.
line_2: Ne'er cease to mention the continu'd Debt,

line_1: And Duty, long as Life, must study to acquit.
line_2: Which the great Patron only would forget,

line_1: All must the just impartial Hand acquit,
line_2: And those who causless murmur — will submit.

line_1: (So ripe was Folly, Folly to acquit)
line_2: Stood all absolv'd in that poor bauble, WIT.
